@node "intro" "Introduction to EmuNet"
@{u}Why was EmuNet written?@{uu}

   After buying a 'big' PC , there was the need for connecting
 both my A3000T and it through network. The simplest  solution 
 would be to buy an Amiga ZorroII/III  network card  , and the
 same for the  PC. However this seemed to be hard , since here
 in  Turkey  , I cannot find any Amiga hardware supplier , and 
 besides those true Amiga network cards are far more expensive 
 than the comparable ones for the PC.So, what I did was simple,
 since I had been using a C= A2386SX Bridgeboard with my Amiga
 for years , I decided to buy two PC network cards and connect
 the new 'big' PC with the emulator board using its  ISA  slot.
 This worked well without a real networking capability between
 the  Amiga & the new PC. I used  most of the  time  the janus
 utils supplied  with A2386 board  to  transfer files  between 
 Amiga & PC. However  this  seemed  to be not the best way  to 
 share resources with both machines.So I  decided  to  write a 
 network  driver  for  the  TCP/IP stack that used the network
 card  of the emulator board ,  as if it belonged to Amiga.

 ============
   HISTORY
 ============

  Searching suitable network driver source code I, came across
 to the well documented  and  easy to  understand  source code
 of  plip38.12 device found on Aminet.  It  is     written and
 (C)  by   Oliver Wagner , Michael  Balzer,  Jeremy  James  as
 mentioned in its documentation.  I  incorparated only  device 
 driver (SANA-2)   backbone of it  and  wrote  the  rest  from  
 scratch. That is  ,   the  communication  with the PC, the PC 
 server  which interfaces  with   the  packet  driver  of  the 
 network  card etc.  are  all written from scratch except some
 of data transfer functions which I took from my other program
 called AmiCDEx.If you do  not know what AmiCDEx is,simply put
 it  interfaces  the   CD-ROM  drive  of  the  Amiga to the PC
 emulator. This   way  you can  use  your  Amiga CD-drive with
 the PC emulator without  buying  a dedicated IDE CD-Drive for
 it. If you  are  interested in this ,  you can find in Aminet
 misc/emu directory. The latest release is 2.2 (AmiCDEx22.lha)
 and has support for C= as well as Goldengate boards.

 EmuNet   driver  should be of interest to  anyone  who has an
 Amiga with a PC/AT emulator board, and other computer(s) with
 which  he/she  wishes  to   connect  via  network in a simple
 (and cheap :) way.

 EmuNet allows you to use your emulator board as an intelligent
 network  card  with  your  Amiga.  The Amiga  network software
 'sees'  a  standard SANA-2 network device driver interface. It 
 does  not know  that the data is re-directed to the PC network
 card.

 If  you wish an overview of the how this driver package works
 take a look at:

              @{" Device Driver Map." link "devicemap" 0}

 See also@{" System Requirements." link "system_req" 0}
@endnode

