@node "versioninfo" "Version information"
 History/Version information.

 This  is  EmuNet v0.9BETA , SANA-II compatible network device
 driver for PC/AT Emulator boards.

-----------------------------------------------------------
 V0.9BETA -  22 July 1998 -  SECOND BETA TEST RELEASE
-----------------------------------------------------------
    Primary update: Speed.. :) I mean it.. The speed that
    the driver achieves has doubled/tripled since the 0.8BETA
    release.
    Cleaned up the source code both for the PC side & the
    Amiga device driver.

    Added new options as well as a new program to let the
    device driver 'read' configuration while it is up 
    and running. 
 ----------------------------------------------------------

--------------------------------------------------------------
 V0.8BETA -   4 July 1998 -   FIRST BETA TEST RELEASE
--------------------------------------------------------------
    Build the driver &  tested successfully with AmiTCP/IP 4.0
    DEMO  which  is  found  on Aminet. I can use  any  network
    software  with  this (namely telnet,ftp, nfs) to with   my
    'big' PC running Linux.
@endnode

@node "installation" "Installing EmuNet"

 -------------------------------------------------------------
  PLEASE NOTE:
  I recommend you to backup your existing TCP/IP configuration
  before messing with this. 
 -------------------------------------------------------------


   Installation  of EmuNet
   =======================

  I  have supplied a simple shell script  (install_for_amitcp)
  to do the standard installation..if you do not like  running
  scripts read it and   figure  out what it does.. The process
  is not so complicated as explained below:

 -------------------------------------------------------------
  1)  copy devs/networks/emunet.device or emunet.device_020 to
      sys:devs/networks/

  2)  add the device driver line for emn0 in file db/interfaces_ADD
      to  AmiTCP:db/interfaces

  3)  copy the bin/emndebug to (preferably) AmiTCP:bin/

  4)  copy EMN_Startnet example script to AmiTCP:bin/
      and edit it to suit your system.

  5)  copy example config file env/sana2/emunet.confog to 
      envarc:sana2/ and env:sana2/

  6)  transfer the emunetd.exe to PC side.
 -------------------------------------------------------------

 That's it. Now go to the @{"configuration & running" link "startingup" 0} section.

 !!! NOTE !!!
 -------------
 There is no builtin version checking of PC & Amiga drivers.
 If you have installed the 0.8BETA drivers remove them before
 intalling new ones.
@endnode

@node "startingup" "Starting EmuNet"

 -------------------------------------------------------------

 NOTE: 
   If  you use my other software   called  AmiCDEx   quit it
  inorder to avoid conflicts for the first time. This is
  not possbile if you used the standard AmiCDEx settings.

 TECHNOTE:
  AmiCDEx uses BOARDOFFSET+0x18500 and EmuNet uses

  BOARDOFFSET+0x18F00 which is far behind to conflict with
  AmiCDEx. However if you use multiple units with AmiCDEx
  you may experience conflicts & should configure EmuNet
  using its  @{" special options " link "configuring" 0}  for this.

 -------------------------------------------------------------
  You should do the @{"installation" link "installation" 0} & @{"configuration " link "configuring" 0}before
  trying to run. 

  ============================
  Starting EmuNet
  ============================
 
 ===============
  PC Emulator
 ===============

 1) Start your packet driver :

    (I have a NE compatible network card  at 0x300    irq 12)

    Example:

    C:\> NE2000 0x60 0xC 0x300

    This   will  install the  packet driver at INT vector  0x60 
    (the usual packet driver INT for PC).


 2) Next, start emunetd.exe with ? to see options..

    C:\> emunetd ?  
  
    or , 

    C:\> emunetd ? >help.txt

   There are many options of emunetd.exe  explained here .

   Just use no   option  with  emunetd   to   let it  run with
   defaults,  or  use   -y3 -i   to enable  asynchronous / irq
   transfers (faster).

   EmuNetD.exe  will search for  the first valid packet driver
   from  0x60 to 0x80 and use the first one found. If you wish
   to use a selected one use the  -p0xINT option.

   If you  have C= Bridgeboard  and emunetd.exe  complains not
   seeing  any  janus  rom (i.e. you do not load janus-handler
   with  PCPrefs  at  the 0xD000)  give  it  -j option to skip
   this test. Infact  emunetd.exe  does  not use any  function
   of janus-handler  currently , but this was a simple test to
   let it know that it is running on a real C= Bridgeboard.

   If you have a Goldengate board you have to  use -g  switch.
   The  default INT  vector  to  report  the  location  of the
   driver to amiga is 0x81.

   You may exit emunetd with ESC key.

   NOTE: That you may safely  quit &  restart emunetd.exe with
   new  options while the emunet.device & Amiga TCP/IP running.
   It  will   not   'hang'  the  amiga-side.  Emunet device on
   Amiga  side  will  notice this and 'suspends'  its  service.
   However it does not go-offline  by default  and  will queue
   send   requests   and   will  retry  to send each packet as
   selected with the  RETRIES  option.

   However due  to the speed  of retries  happening, any  data
   send   from  Amiga TCP/IP  stack will    be lost  when  the
   emunetd.exe is not  active for a long time on PC side.

 -------------------------------------------------------------

  ===========
     Amiga
  ===========

   Start the interface (emn0) & TCP/IP stack with the supplied
   script.

   emunet.device will popup a window printing some information
   and closing after a while. If the device driver initializes
   successfully you will see a short 'green' color.

   From now on you can test if this works for you:
    
   Suppose  you  have a Linux box with a network interface and
   configured IP address 192.168.0.1 (see the db/rc.inet1 file
   for an example linux config).

   ping 192.168.0.1

   If it replies then ping Amiga from other side,(assuming you
   used  the  example startnet  script with default  options).

   ping 192.168.0.3

   If you see Amiga replies then the driver seems to be running
   ok and you may use other network  software  such  as telnet,
   ftp,nfs etc.

   Well if it does not function as mentioned  you  may  use the
   supplied freeware  sanautil  to test if the  device can send
   and receive data  from other side.
   
   Go to the debug section for further information on this.

 -------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode

@node "configuring" "Configuring AmICDEx"
 ========================================================
           EmuNet Configuration options
 ========================================================

  emunetd.exe config options are explained  @{"  here  " link "config_pc" 0} .

  emunet.device once invoked will try to read the file

   env:sana2/emunet.config

  If it cannot find this file it uses the default builtin
  options. Simply use one of the supplied config files
  found in env/sana2/ directory.

 Current configuration template looks like this:

  TIMEOUT/K/N,POLLWAIT/K/N,PRIORITY=PRI/K/N,
  MTU/K/N,BPS/K/N,RETRIES/K/N,ASYNC/K/N,CHUNKSIZE/K/N,
  BASEADDR=BADR/K,BOARDADDR/K,GOLDENIRQ=GIRQ/K
  ETHERADR/K,QUICKWRITE/S,READTASK/S,AMIGAGOLDEN/S,DEBUG/S,COLORS/S

  
  TIMEOUT=n  (Default 1000000)
 
  Determines  the count down  value    used during   low level
  data transfers  to/from PC. Most   of the  time this  is not
  used , however when a r/w request does not  satisfy   within
  this countdown it is assumed that send/receive failed.
  The usual range should be betweeen   100000-1000000 ,    the
  higher  the value the longer the device 'stucks' waiting for
  the PC side to respond. The same option may be given to the
  PC driver with -t<number>.

  POLLWAIT=n

  Whenever a packet is received the driver 'polls' the message
  base in the hope that successive packets will  arrive.  This
  reduces the response time of the device  driver.  The  usual
  range is between 1-100. Do not use high   values since  this
  reduces overall performance & consumes  much more CPU  time.

  PRIORITY=n (Default 15)

  The task priority  of emunet.device  device  dispatcher. All
  suitable network  requests to the devices are re-directed to
  this task. The default  value  is 15 , you may select values
  up to 25 , but do not use higher values than 30.


  MTU=n  (Default 1500)

  MaximumTransferUnit .   A  single  packet  cannot  be bigger
  than the value specified here. The Amiga device driver  uses 
  the value which is reported by the PC packet driver. However
  my packet   driver  reports this to be -1. If  emunet.device 
  detects this it defaults to 1500, which  is the most  common
  value used with ethernet  boards. 

  Note that the MTU value of the emunet.device must match with
  that of other  computer(s) connected to your network.

  RETRIES=n (Default 63)

  Determines  how  many  times the device dispatcher will retry
  to send each packet before throwing it away.


  ASYNC=b (Default 3)

  
  This is a   flag  register  allowing to  set the async/sync
  transfers between Amiga & PC.

  0 -> No change to previous setting.
  1 -> PC--> Amiga async
  2 -> Amiga->PC   async
  4 -> PC--> Amiga sync
  8 -> Amiga->PC   sync
 
  Since this is a flag register you may add each value like, 
  1+8=9 to enable both of the above functions. Async option
  overrides  sync  one  (i.e if you give 15 both Amiga & PC
  use async transfers).
  
  The same option can be set using emunetd.exe -yN parameter.

  Note that the  last    change to this option will be used.
  That is if  you set it  to 15 during emunet.device startup
  using env:sana2/emunet.config , and stop &   restart   the
  emunetd.exe with a new value of -yN this will be   used by
  both sides.

  CHUNKSIZE=n [0-255] (Default 0= interpreted as 256)

  Each async transfer as explained above will use this as a
  base for chunky transfers. The async stuff seems to increase
  the driver speed considerably. Simply use the max value
  0 , which is interpreted as 256 and 15 for ASYNC and forget
  all about this :)


  BASEADDR=BADDR=0xdirect_address.

  Override any board detection & use this address as message base.

  If emunet.device does not detect your board you may start it
  using this option. BEWARE: No check is done , and emunet.device
  directly plays with the given address. You may consider to
  specify a suitable base address for the emunetd.exe using its
  -a0xdirect_address option.

  BOARDADDR=0xboard_base.

  If emunet.device does not detect your board, you may give the
  start address (i.e. in Zorro-II space) of it. This will   let 
  the driver to use default offsets. Note: For vortex/goldengat
  you should also specifiy GOLDENIRQ=0x81 option. 

 
  GOLDENIRQ=GIRQ=n

  Used to switch the driver into goldengate mode manually and specify
  a PC IRQ vector to use inorder to locate emunetd.exe in PC memory. 
  Normally emunet should detect this and act accordingly. But if 
  this fails, you may force it to switch to Goldengate operation 
  & use the given IRQ vector. Use the default value 0x81 first.


  ETHERADDR=0xAA:0xBB:0xCC:0xDD:0xEE:0xFF

  Hardware related  six bytes ethernet address to use. Normally you 
  don't need  this since emunet.device learns this from your PC 
  packet  driver via emunetd.exe.


  QUICKWRITE/S

  If the IOF_QUICK device flag should be used or not. Normally
  every R/W request from emunet.device is queued to the Device
  dispatcher task which handles them quiet fast. If you wish
  that all writes are done immediately use this option.

  NOTE: I do not recommend the use of this.. Since this may
  stuck the device driver if the PC side cannot respond quickly.
  
  READTASK/S

  If the emunet.device should use a seperate reader task. I
  thought this would speed the transfers a lot but it does not
  due to the PC packet driver nature. They cannot handle
  read/writes at the same time quiet well. So do not use
  this option or the performance of the driver may drop a lot
  due to competing WRITER & READER tasks which will be active
  at the same time.


  AMIGAGOLDEN/S

  Do not use this. Since I do not have any Goldengate board to 
  test those features I simply 'emulated' a goldengate board
  using C= bridgeboard. So this is not for users :)


  DEBUG/S

  Well if you need this.. Use along with emndebug program.

  COLORS/S

  Nice screen colors showing the activity of the device driver.

  Give this and do a 'big' ftp transfer & watch the screenshow :)

  Infact this is much more helpfull than lots of DEBUG outputs
  to 'see' that the device functions properly , and also a simple
  way to judge its speed (the faster the colors change the faster
  the data transfers are done).

  -------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode

@node "todo" "Things I plan to implement in EmuNet"
@{u}To do@{uu}
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
 If you have any reasonable suggestions, please mail them 
 to the @{"author" link "author" 0}.

 --------------------------------


 -Support for 'virtual' network feature as suggested by 
  a user but took longer than expected to implement in this
  release. Simply put this feature would enable to run a 
  'virtual' LAN inside Amiga. That is each program that
  opens a specific unit of emunet.device would be able
  to communicate with other units of it. This way, 
  for example one would use Shapeshifter & Amiga TCP/IP
  at the same time.

 -Multiple PC network card support.

   (Huh?, Does anyone need this ?)

 - Use it as a simple 'virtual' connection  to  share Amiga &
   PC Emulator resources. This is also suggested  by a user
   but the primary purpose of the driver was  not with  this
   in mind since I  do not use my 386SX board  for   serious
   stuff. If the wish list for this goes high :^) ,  I  may
   well consider  implementing this.

 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
 See @{"Bugs/Limitations" link "bugs_limitations" 0}.
@endnode

@node "featurelist" "Why should I use EmuNet?"

 Here is a list of the main features of EmuNet, to let you see at 
 a glance what it can do for you. More detailed feature list can be
 found in @{"version info" link "versioninfo" 0}.

------------------------------------------------------------
 Feature list (for version 0.9BETA)
------------------------------------------------------------

        Improved speed..  The   overall performance of the 
        driver doubled/tripled with the same hardware. 
        This  was achieved with smart buffering of  packets 
        with a lot more optimized transfer routines between
        Amiga & the PC.

------------------------------------------------------------
 Feature list (for version 0.8BETA)
------------------------------------------------------------
        Small bug fixes.
        Works with Workbench 2 or 3
        Uses PC/AT Network card to interface to Amiga TCP/IP 
        stack.
        Tested with AmiTCP 4.0 DEMO and a Linux/W95 box.
        Many options to optimize transfer speed.
        Well for the first beta what do you expect more ? :-)
--------------------------------------------------------
@endnode

