 ========================================================
                 EmuNet Device Driver Map
 ========================================================

  Amiga with a PC hardware emulator and a PC network card
          |
          |         
  Amiga TCP/IP <======> emunet.device                           
                            |                                  
                            |                                  
                PC  EmunetD driver <===> Packet Driver
                                               |          
                                               |          
         Your Local NetWork <=======> PC Network Interface
                |                                          
                |                                          
   Linux box                and/or,
   W*n   PC                 and/or,
   Another Amiga  with a true Zorro2/3 Network  card   and/or,
   Another Amiga with a PC hardware emulator and  a PC network
   card :)

 ========================================================
@endnode

@node "debug" " Debug"

 =========================
   Solving Problems
 =========================

   Well you installed EmuNet as  described  and  tried to  run
   it  but it did not function as mentioned.  So what to   do?
   Here I am giving some simple steps to find out whether  the
   problem   relates to  EmuNet  and/or  it  to  your  network 
   configuration or hardware.

  *Please note that  I  am  not  a  network  guru in  terms of
   programming  &  configuration  of  all  the  various  stuff
   related   with it. So if you do not have any information on 
   how to install TCP/IP & configure your simple LAN, seek the
   help  of a friend before reporting that the driver does not
   function.

   You  may  use the supplied freeware sanautil to test if the
   device can send and receive data from other computer(s)
   connected to your PC Emulator through ethernet.


1) 
   copy the debug config env/sana2/emunet.config_DEBUG  to
   env:sana2/emunet.config
   2) Next  stop the  TCP/IP (stopnet) , and issue a  offline emn0
   command. Then  do  a  'avail flush' * TWICE! * to remove the
   device  from memory.If the device is removed from memory the
   screen  will  flash  red for  a short time  which  indicates
   that   DeviceExpunge()'ed  from  memory. The   next time you
   start the device it  will read the new   debug configuration
   that you just copied.

3)  Stop  emunetd.exe on the PC side (ESC key)  and  restart it
    with -d -u (debug , dump) along with others you use.

4)  Open a newshell window and start the bin/emndebug program.

5)  Start the emunet.device with the supplied sanautil. (Do not
    start it with TCP/IP stack using EMN_StartNet script).

    sanautil DEVICE=emunet.device ONLINE
    
    As usual the screen  will flash  green &  the popup window
    appears.

6)  Start a packet dump utility on your other network computer
    (if it is a PC then use the pcbin/pktall util , if it is an
    Amiga use the same sanautil with the network device driver
    of this (e.g. a2065.device)  and DUMP option).
   7)  Issue a broadcast message to the network
   
    sanautil DEVICE=emunet.device BROADCAST

8)  The emndebug screen will print lots of debug output. See if 
    the BROADCAST message arrives to other network computer. 

   ==========================
    Reverse  the procedure:
   ==========================

1)  Start sanautil watching for packets to arrive:
   
    sanautil DEVICE=emunet.device DUMP
   2)  Then send with an  appropriate  util packets  from network
    computer to PC  Emulator  and hence   the Amiga. If   your
    networked computer is a PC simply use the supplied pktsend
    command, or if it is an Amiga use the sanautil to broadcast
    messages  (e.g. sanautil device=a2065.device BROADCAST, do
    not forget to bring the device ONLINE first!).
    
   ==========================
     RESULT
   ==========================

    If both sides can send and recieve  packets  this  way and
    your  TCP/IP software does not work , then  I  suggest you
    to  check your network configuration , both on  Amiga  and
    the other  network computer you are communicating  with.

    Well,  if nothing   helps   repeat  the debug procedure as
    explained  below.   Inorder  to  quit  a  running emndebug 
    program, the emunet.device should be removed from memory.

    sanautil DEVICE=emunet.device OFFLINE

    avail FLUSH (remember do this TWICE!)
 
    and you should see screen flashing red. If you started the
    emndebug with TCP/IP running then use the usual 'stopnet' &
    'avail FLUSH' procedure.

    Re-start emndebug, but this time redirecting its output to
    a file: 

    emndebug >ram:debug_file

    and repeat the debug procedure starting from 5).

    Then send the debug file to   me with  E-Mail along with the 
    detailed description of your hardware & software.

    Note :  If the resulting debug file is too large (>5k) 
    please compress & uuencode it  before sending.

--------------------------------------------------------
@endnode

@node "system_req" " System Requirements"
 @{u}System Requirements@{uu}

------------------------------------------------------- 
 Hardware :

  -- an Amiga :)

  -- a  PC Emulator board.

  -- a  PC network  card.

  -- other  computer/computers that  are  connected to your PC
     network  card ,  and   are  able  to  talk  with  TCP/IP.

     Examples include:
     - a  386/486/586  class machine (Linux  box , W*n95 etc.)
     - another   Amiga  with  a true ZORRO  2/3  network  card
     - if  you  happen to be (un)lucky enough :) another Amiga
       with a  PC  emulator board and another PC network card.
--------------------------------------------------------
 Software :

  -- WB 2 or 3

  -- A  TCP/IP  stack (tested successfully with AmiTCP4.0 DEMO
     which is available on Aminet)

  -- The EmuNet device driver files..
       emndebug
       EMN_Startnet
       emunet.device or emunet.device_020
       emunet.config
       emunetd.exe (PC exe)
  -- EmuNet just requires a functioning packet driver for your
     PC network card.

   This should be included in the driver disk  that came  with
   your network card. If you do not have a packet   driver for 
   your card, I have included the free NE2000 packet driver as
   most of the PC network cards are claiming  to be compatible
   with this. If it does not function with your network  card,
   see the 'HOWTOGET.IT' file in pcbin directory to  learn how
   to get the full Crynwr packet driver distribution.
--------------------------------------------------------
@endnode

@node "config_pc" " EmuNetD.exe configuration "
 ============================================================
  EmuNetD.exe configuration 
 ============================================================

 Emunetd.exe uses command line to configure itself, no special
 file is used for this. So simply write a .bat file with your
 usual options and use this to start it. You may get a list of
 available options using emunetd.exe -? >help.txt

  -----PACKET DRIVER --------------------------------------

     -pPKTINT         Use this packet driver IRQ (default 0x60)
     -mPKTMODE        Put packet driver into mode. (default 6=ALL)
                      (See your packet driver docs!)

                        1)RCV OFF        2) RCV THIS   3)+BCAST
                        4)+MCAST Limited 5)+MCAST Full 6)ALL

     -bMAXRINGBUFS    Number of cyclic buffers to use
     -eMAXRETRIES     Max number of retries before packets thrown away.
     -fFLUSHCOUNT     Flush count at a time for ring buffers
     -i[n]            Use IRQ flush (n=1 PC->Amiga 2=Amiga->PC 3=Both) [1]
     -u               Dump each packet received/sent
     -s               Ring stream show.

  -------AMIGA SPECIFIC -------------------------------------

     -a0xBASEADDR     Use 0xBASEADDR to communicate with emunet.device
     -g[0xIRQ]        Switch to GoldenGate mode & use IRQ # [0x81]
     -x               TEST AMIGA golden
     -y[f]            Asynchronous transfer bits:
                      1=PC->AMIGA 2=AMIGA->PC  3=BOTH 0=NONE [0xF]
     -tCOUNTER        Asynchronous transfer wait
     -cBYTES          Chunk size each asynchronous transfer (0-255) [0=256]
     -wCOUNTER        Poll counter for msg. base to decrease response time [32]
     -j               Do not check for janus-handler (for C= boards).
     -k               Transfer one way at a time (half-duplex)
     -v               Verbose operation.
    -------GENERIC ------------------------------------------
     -r                     Install as TSR (pop key is ALT-E
     -rt             Install as TCR (run in background)
     -ru             Uninstall running TCR
     -rk             Explicit kill of TSR/TCR (dangerous)
     -d              DEBUG


WARNING: Do not use TSR/TCR options .. They do not function as expected and you may
crash your machine. This also reduces the transfer speed considerably which is
probably not what you want. If you wish to use the PC emulator, simply quit
emunetd.exe with ESC key and restart after it after you are done. Note that this will
not hang Amiga side.

Also do not use -b with values greater  than  12.  It  does not speed things up very
much after a certain value (e.g. 8).
@endnode

@node "performance" " Performance              "
 ===================================================
 PERFORMANCE
 ===================================================

 I have achieved  FTP  transfer  speeds from a 586 PC->Amiga
 around 280kb/sec and  Amiga->PC  ~240 kb/sec.   Appearantly
 the 'polling'  feature of the PC driver  does  affect   the
 Amiga->PC  transfer speeds.  It is  also  slowed down  with 
 a  386SX-25Mhz  emulator  board  considerably.I do not know 
 what  speeds   may be achived if  you  just use a 286 class 
 emulator board or a CPU upgraded  486SX emulator board.

 I measured tha *RAW* TCP/IP socket communication with a quick
 hack program@{" (stest) " link "support_prog" 0} written for this purpose and achieved 
 the results in 1. below.

 Please report your results along with your hardware/software
 description and EmuNet configuration so that I can expand this
 table on later releases.

 (Do not forget to include your EmuNet configuration
 as the performance depens heavily on it).

 ================================================================
 | Amiga       | Emulator | Net Comp.  |Amiga->Net | Net->Amiga |
 ================================================================
 01. 68030/25  | 386SX/25 | AMDK6/233  | 320 K/sec |  340 K/sec
@endnode

@node "support_prog" " Support  Programs        "
 ====================================================
 OTHER SUPPORT PROGRAMS FOUND IN ARCHIVE
 ====================================================
 
 bin/emndebug
 ------------

 This program is used along with the DEBUG option of 
 emunet.config . See the debugging section for info.

 bin/emnsig
 ------------

 This is just a 'signal' command which lets already
 running emunet.device read its config file   again.
 If you change parameters in env:sana2/emunet.config 
 file while your network is already up & running
 you can simply use this program instead of 'stopnet'
 'avail FLUSH' 'startnet' sequence.
 
 bin/sanamon
 ------------

 Written by Michael van Elst , useful Sana2 device packet
 monitor program. See bin/sanamon.readme for further info.

 bin/sanautil
 ------------

 Written by Timo Rossi testing/debugging tool for SANA2
 network device drivers. Read /bin/sanautil.doc for further
 info.

 pcbin/NE2000.COM
 ----------------

 A free  NE*000 compatible packet driver.


 pcbin/PKTALL.COM
 ----------------

 A free packet driver monitor for PC. Dumps received packets.

 pcbin/PKTSEND.COM
 ----------------

 A free packet send/broadcast utility for PC.

 --------------------
 socket/stest                (Amiga executable using ixemul.library)
 socket/stest_linux_i386.ELF (i386 Linux executable)
 socket/stest.c              (source code of stest)
 socket/mk                   (simple make script)

 A simple program that does raw data transfers using BSD sockets. 
 This was a quick hack , inorder to measure RAW transfer speeds
 of EmuNet without the overhead of another protocol (e.g. ftp/nfs).
 stest can run in two modes : first is the server mode which
 waits & accepts connection on a specified port (def. 50000),and
 second as the client for an already running stest instance. 
 Note that both instances may be run on the same host (this
 would let you see the 'raw' loopback speed of your network).

 I have compiled two versions of it, so you can use it directly
 if you have a pc linux box. I wished to include another PC exe
 which used w*95 but I do not have the necessary tools for this.
 (Note: I could compile it with a beta bsdsocket emulation library
 which uses w*95 & DJGPP but it crashed).

 You have the source code, if you succeed to compile & run it
 with w*95 please send    me    a copy.

 ====================================================
 How to make speed test with this:
 ====================================================

 (Assuming TCP/IP is up & running)

 Start an instance of stest on Amiga using: 

 1> stest -s

 This will take over your shell , and wait for connections to be
 made.

 Go to another shell  & start it with no options:

 2> stest

 This will connect to the previous one and you should see
 how fast the transfer is made (default 2 Meg. RAW data transfer)
 is done. 

 Use stest -? to get a list of supported options.

 Now if you have a linux box up & running connected with
 emunet (or any other means via TCP/IP)

 Start a server in background:

 $. stest -s  & 
 
 Next do a test with this:
 
 $. stest 

 You should see both server & client output comes to the same
 console saying the results obtained (this is quite fast with
 p5 class machines). 
 
 Now try to connect with Amiga:

 $. stest -n<your.amiga.net.addr>

 and the PC from Amiga:

 2> stest -n<your.powerfull.pc.addr>


 You may optionally supply -r (random data) and -edata_to_be_transferredK
 
 if you feel that default (-e2048 i.e. 2Meg) is not big enough.
  
 You may also use the -c option to see that the data can be reliably
 transferred between each host. (Do not use this while measuring
 speed, since this brings another impact on transfer speed).

 ====================================================================
@endnode

